Day-1: Linux Basics - DevOps Foundation

Introduction to Linux in DevOps

Why Linux is Crucial for DevOps?

-Foundation of DevOps: 90%+ DevOps tools & pipelines Linux-based hai

-Cloud Compatibility: AWS, Azure, GCP ke servers mostly Linux pe chalti hain

-Automation Friendly: Scripting aur automation Linux me natural fit hai

-Containerization: Docker, Kubernetes Linux kernel pe depend karte hain


File System Navigation Commands
Basic Directory Operations

pwd   ------------------- >   Present Working Directory - current location
ls    -------------------->   List files/folders (basic)
ls -l -------------------->   Detailed list with permissions
ls -la ------------------->   All files including hidden ones
cd <directory> --------------->  Change directory
cd .. ------------------------>  Parent directory me jao
cd ~  ------------------------>  Home directory me jao


File & Folder Management

mkdir devopswar ---------------->              New folder create karna
touch day1.txt ----------------->              Empty file create karna
rm day1.txt  ------------------->              File delete karna
rm -r devopswar  --------------->              Folder aur uski contents delete karna
cp file1.txt file2.txt ------------------>     Copy file
mv file1.txt newname.txt ---------------->     Rename/Move file


ðŸ” File Permissions & Ownership (Detailed)
Permission Structure

-rw-r--r-- 1 user group 0 Apr 15 10:00 day1.txt
â””â”€â”¬â”€â”˜ â””â”€â”¬â”€â”˜ â””â”€â”¬â”€â”˜
  â”‚     â”‚     â””â”€â”€ Others: r-- = read only
  â”‚     â””â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€ Group: r-- = read only  
  â””â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€ Owner: rw- = read + write


Permission Codes
#	        Permission	       File	                                  Directory
0	        ---	               No access	                            No access
1	        --x	               Execute	                              Access only
2	        -w-	               Write	                                Create/delete
3	        -wx	               Write+Execute	                        Modify contents
4	        r--	               Read	                                  List contents
5	        r-x	               Read+Execute	                          List & access
6	        rw-	               Read+Write	                            List & modify
7	        rwx	               All	                                  Full control


chmod Examples

chmod 644 day1.txt        # Owner: RW, Group: R, Others: R
chmod 755 script.sh       # Owner: RWX, Group: RX, Others: RX
chmod 700 secret.txt      # Only owner can access
chmod +x script.sh        # Add execute permission to all


Ownership Commands

whoami                               # Current user ka naam
id                                   # User aur group details
sudo chown user:group file.txt       # Owner aur group change karna
sudo chgrp devops file.txt           # Group change karna


ðŸ“ Text Editors for DevOps
Nano (Beginner Friendly)

nano day1.txt             # File open/edit karna
# Ctrl + O â†’ Save
# Ctrl + X â†’ Exit
# Ctrl + K â†’ Cut line
# Ctrl + U â†’ Paste


Vim (Advanced - DevOps me commonly use hota hai)

vim day1.txt              # Open in Vim
# i â†’ Insert mode
# Esc â†’ Command mode
# :w â†’ Save
# :q â†’ Quit
# :wq â†’ Save & Quit
# :q! â†’ Force quit without saving


ðŸ’¾ System Monitoring Commands
Disk & Storage

df -h                     # Disk free space (human readable)
du -sh *                  # Directory sizes in current location
du -h --max-depth=1       # Subdirectory sizes

# Examples output:
# Filesystem      Size  Used Avail Use% Mounted on
# /dev/sda1        20G   15G  3.8G  80% /


Process & System Info

top                       # Live system processes
htop                      # Better version of top (install karna padega)
ps aux                    # All running processes
free -h                  # RAM usage
uptime                   # System uptime & load average


ðŸš€ DevOps-Specific Linux Concepts

1. SSH (Secure Shell)

ssh username@server_ip    # Remote server connect karna
ssh-keygen               # SSH keys generate karna (GitHub, servers ke liye)

2. Package Management

# Ubuntu/Debian
sudo apt update
sudo apt install git docker nginx

# RHEL/CentOS
sudo yum update
sudo yum install git docker

3. Service Management

sudo systemctl start nginx     # Service start karna
sudo systemctl stop nginx      # Service stop karna
sudo systemctl status nginx    # Service status check karna
sudo systemctl enable nginx    # Boot time pe auto-start ke liye

4. Logs Dekhna (Debugging ke liye important)

tail -f /var/log/syslog        # Live logs dekho
cat /var/log/auth.log          # Authentication logs
journalctl -xe                 # Systemd logs


Day-1 Summary Checklist --------

->  Basic navigation commands (pwd, ls, cd)

-> File operations (touch, mkdir, rm)

-> File permissions (chmod, ls -l)

-> Text editing (nano)

-> System info (df, whoami)

-> GitHub pe notes upload kiye

_> Homework: man command se 2 commands ka manual padho (e.g., man ls, man chmod)

Pro Tip: Linux me "RTFM" (Read The F* Manual) culture hai. man <command> ya <command> --help se detailed help milti hai. Kabhi bhi atak jao toh manual check karo!




